name: cystathionine beta-lyase
classes: Carbon-sulfur lyases (only sub-subclass identified to date)
reaction: L-cystathionine + H2O = L-homocysteine + pyruvate + NH3 (overall reaction) [RN:R01286]; (1a) L-cystathionine = L-homocysteine + 2-aminoprop-2-enoate; (1b) 2-aminoprop-2-enoate = 2-iminopropanoate (spontaneous); (1c) 2-iminopropanoate + H2O = pyruvate + NH3 (spontaneous)
comment: A pyridoxal-phosphate protein. The enzyme cleaves a carbon-sulfur bond, releasing L-homocysteine and an unstable enamine product that tautomerizes to an imine form, which undergoes a hydrolytic deamination to form pyruvate and ammonia. The latter reaction, which can occur spontaneously, can also be catalysed by EC 3.5.99.10, 2-iminobutanoate/2-iminopropanoate deaminase. The enzyme from some sources also acts on L-cystine, forming pyruvate, ammonia and cysteine persulfide, and a number of related compounds. Possibly identical, in yeast, with EC 4.4.1.6 S-alkylcysteine lyase.

references.title: Cystine lyase: beta-cystathionase from turnip roots.
